$P = Point(2,2,2); $v = Vector(2,2,-1);
$t = Formula("t"); $line = Vector("$P + $t * $v");
$evaluatorforline= ParametricLine("$line")->cmp();
############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML Find a vector equation for the line in the direction of [`\vec{v}=2\vec{i} +2\vec{j} -\vec{k}`] passing through the point [`(2,2,2)\text{.}`]
[`\vec{r}(t)=`] [_]{$evaluatorforline}{15} [@AnswerFormatHelp('vectors')@]*
END_PGML
############################################################ # Hint ############################################################ #Set value of $showHint in PGcourse.pl for course-wide attempt threshhold for revealing hints
BEGIN_PGML_HINT Recall that a vector equation for a line passing through point [`P`] at [`t=0`] in the direction of the vector [`\vec{v}`] is [`\vec{r}(t)=\vec{P} +\vec{v}t`] where [`\vec{P}`] is the position vector with head at point [`P\text{.}`]
END_PGML_HINT
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION A vector equation for the line in the direction of [`\vec{v}=2\vec{i} +2\vec{j} -\vec{k}`] passing through the point [`P=(2,2,2)`] at [`t=0`] is \\\[\\vec\{r\}(t)=\\vec\{P\}\+t\\vec\{v\},\\\] where [`\vec{P}`] is the position vector with head at point [`P\text{.}`] Thus we get
[```\newcommand{\amp}{&}\begin{aligned} \vec{r}(t)\amp =2\vec{i}+2\vec{j}+2\vec{k}+t(2\vec{i} +2\vec{j} -\vec{k}) \\ \amp =(2+2t)\vec{i} +(2+2t)\vec{j} +(2-t)\vec{k}. \end{aligned}```]
END_PGML_SOLUTION
############################################################ # End Problem ############################################################
ENDDOCUMENT();

setup.pg-code:
Context("Vector");
Context()->variables->are(t=>"Real");

$P = Point(1,2,3);
$Q = Point(3,2,1);
$PQ = Vector(2,0,-2);

$t = Formula("t");
$line = Vector("$P + $t * $PQ");

$multians = MultiAnswer( $line, Real("0"), Real("1") )->with(
  singleResult => 0,
  checker => sub {
    my ( $correct, $student, $ansHash ) = @_;
    my ( $linestu, $astu, $bstu ) = @{$student};
    my ( $linecor, $acor, $bcor ) = @{$correct};

    if ( (ParametricLine("$line") == $linestu) and
         ($linestu->eval(t=>$astu) == $line->eval(t=>"0")) and
         ($linestu->eval(t=>$bstu) == $line->eval(t=>"1")) ) 
    {  
       return [1,1,1]; 

    } elsif ( (ParametricLine("$line") == $linestu) and
              ($linestu->eval(t=>$astu) == $line->eval(t=>"0")) )
    {  
       return [1,1,0]; 

    } elsif ( (ParametricLine("$line") == $linestu) and
              ($linestu->eval(t=>$bstu) == $line->eval(t=>"1")) )
    {  
       return [1,0,1]; 

    } elsif ( (ParametricLine("$line") == $linestu) )
    {
        return [1,0,0];

    } else { 
        return [0,0,0]; 
    }

  }
);

solution.p:

The vector pointing from (1,2,3) to (3,2,1) is \vec{v}=2\vec{i} -2\vec{k}. Therefore, a vector equation for this line segment will be 

    \vec{r}(t)=\vec{i} +2\vec{j} +3\vec{k} +(2\vec{i} -2\vec{k})t=(1+2t)\vec{i} +2\vec{j} +(3-2t)\vec{k}

with 0\leq t\leq 1.

