BEGIN_PGML
Find a vector equation for a quarter circle centered at [`(0,0)`] of radius [`3`] starting at the point [`(3,0)`] and oriented counter-clockwise.

[`x(t) =`] [_]{$multians}{10} [@AnswerFormatHelp('formulas')@]*

[`y(t) =`] [_]{$multians}{10} [@AnswerFormatHelp('formulas')@]*

for [_]{$multians}{3} [`\leq t \leq `] [_]{$multians}{3} [@AnswerFormatHelp('numbers')@]*

END_PGML

############################################################
# Hint
############################################################
#Set value of $showHint in PGcourse.pl for course-wide attempt threshhold for revealing hints

BEGIN_PGML_HINT
Recall that [`\vec{r}(t) =\cos t \vec{i} +\sin t \vec{j}\text{,}`] [`0\leq t\leq 2\pi`] gives a full circle oriented counter-clockwise starting (when [`t=0`]) at [`(1,0)\text{.}`]

END_PGML_HINT

############################################################
# Solution
############################################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
The equation [`\vec{r}(t) =\cos t \vec{i} +\sin t \vec{j}\text{,}`] [`0\leq t\leq 2\pi`] gives a full circle of radius [`1`] oriented counter-clockwise starting at [`(1,0)`] when [`t=0\text{.}`] To get a circle of radius [`3\text{,}`] we scale each component by [`3\text{.}`] Thus [`\vec{r}(t) =3\cos t \vec{i} +3\sin t \vec{j}`] for [`0\leq t\leq 2\pi`] is a circle of radius [`3`] centered at [`(0,0)`] oriented counterclockwise starting at [`(0,3)`] when [`t=0\text{.}`] To get the quarter circle, we restrict [`0\leq t\leq \pi/2\text{.}`]

END_PGML_SOLUTION

############################################################
# End Problem
############################################################

ENDDOCUMENT();

setup.pg-code:
Context("Numeric");
Context()->variables->are(t=>"Real");
Context()->variables->set(t=>{limits=>[-1,1]});

$x = Formula("1+2*cos(t)");
$y = Formula("4");
$z = Formula("1+2*sin(t)");
$t0 = Compute("0");
$t1 = Compute("pi");

($x0,$y0,$z0) = (3,4,1);
($x1,$y1,$z1) = (-1,4,1);

$multians = MultiAnswer($x, $y, $z, $t0, $t1)->with(
  singleResult => 0,
  checker => sub {
      my ( $correct, $student, $self ) = @_;
      my ( $xstu, $ystu, $zstu, $t0stu, $t1stu ) = @{$student};
      if ( 
           ( ( ($xstu-1)**2+($ystu-4)**2+($zstu-1)**2 ) == 4 )  and
           ( ($xstu->eval(t=>$t0stu)) == $x0 ) and
           ( ($ystu->eval(t=>$t0stu)) == $y0 ) and
           ( ($xstu->eval(t=>$t1stu)) == $x1 ) and
           ( ($ystu->eval(t=>$t1stu)) == $y1 )
         ) {
            return [1,1,1,1,1];

      } elsif (
           ( ( ($xstu-1)**2+($ystu-4)**2+($zstu-1)**2 ) == 4 )  and
           ( ($xstu->eval(t=>$t0stu)) == $x0 ) and
           ( ($ystu->eval(t=>$t0stu)) == $y0 ) 
         ) { 
            return [1,1,1,1,0];

      } elsif (
           ( ( ($xstu-1)**2+($ystu-4)**2+($zstu-1)**2 ) == 4 )  and
           ( ($xstu->eval(t=>$t1stu)) == $x1 ) and
           ( ($ystu->eval(t=>$t1stu)) == $y1 )
         ) { 
            return [1,1,1,0,1];

      } elsif (
           ( ( ($xstu-1)**2+($ystu-4)**2+($zstu-1)**2 ) == 4 ) 
         ) { 
            return [1,1,1,0,0];

      } else {
            return [0,0,0,0];
      }
  }
);

solution.p:
The equation \vec{r}(t) =\cos t \vec{i} +\sin t \vec{k}, 0\leq t\leq 2\pi gives a full circle oriented counter-clockwise starting (when t=0) at (1,0,0) in the xz-plane. To get a circle of radius 2, we scale each component by 2, and to move the center to (1,4,1) we add the vector \vec{i} +4\vec{j}+\vec{k} (which translates every point in the x-direction by 1, the y-direction by 4 and the z-direction by 1).  Thus 

    \vec{r}(t) =(1+2\cos t)\vec{i} +4\vec{j}+(1+ 2\sin(t))\vec{k}

for 0\leq t\leq 2\pi is a circle of radius 2 centered at  (1,4,1) in the plane y=4 starting at the point (3,2,1).  To get the half circle, we restrict 0\leq t\leq \pi.

