BEGIN_PGML
Find a vector equation for the segment of the graph of [`y=x^3`] starting at [`(2,8)`] to the point [`(-1,-1)\text{.}`]

[`x(t) =`] [_]{$multians}{10} [@AnswerFormatHelp('formulas')@]*

[`y(t) =`] [_]{$multians}{10} [@AnswerFormatHelp('formulas')@]*

for [_]{$multians}{3} [`\leq t \leq `] [_]{$multians}{3} [@AnswerFormatHelp('numbers')@]*

END_PGML

############################################################
# Hint
############################################################
#Set value of $showHint in PGcourse.pl for course-wide attempt threshhold for revealing hints

BEGIN_PGML_HINT
Recall that to parameterize a curve that follows that graph of a function [`y=f(x)`] oriented from right to left, we can choose [`x=-t`] and then [`y`] is completely determined by the function [`y=f(x)\text{.}`]

END_PGML_HINT

############################################################
# Solution
############################################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
To parameterize a curve that follows that graph of a function [`y=f(x)`] oriented from right to left, we can choose [`x=-t`] and  then we get [`y=f(-t)=-t^3\text{.}`] Thus, [`\vec{r}(t) =-t\vec{i} -t^3\vec{j}`] is a vector equation for  [`y=x^3`] oriented from right to left. Since [`x=-t`] we choose [`-2\leq t\leq 1`] to restrict to the appropriate domain.

END_PGML_SOLUTION

############################################################
# End Problem
############################################################

ENDDOCUMENT();

