BEGIN_PGML For the given vector field [`\vec{F}`] and curve [`C`] (oriented from left to right), determine whether [`\int_{C} \vec{F} \cdot d\vec{r}`] is positive, negative, or zero.
[`\int_{C} \vec{F} \cdot d\vec{r}`] is [_]{$MC1}{5}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Hint ############################################################ #Set value of $showHint in PGcourse.pl for course-wide attempt threshhold for revealing hints
BEGIN_PGML_HINT Recall that the integral [`\int_{C} \vec{F} \cdot d\vec{r}`] is a scalar measurement of how the vector field [`\vec{F}`] flows along the oriented curve [`C`] [$MDASH]* it is positive when it generally flows with the curve, negative when it flows against and zero when it is perpendicular or flows roughly equally with it and against it.
END_PGML_HINT
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION In the second quadrant, the vector field flows roughly in the same direction as the curve, and in the first quadrant it flows perpendicular. Therefore the integral is positive.
END_PGML_SOLUTION
############################################################ # End Problem ############################################################
