############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML Evaluate [`\displaystyle \int_{C} \left( x\vec{i} -y\vec{j} \right) \cdot d\vec{r}`] where [`C`] is the line segment from [`(2,3)`] to [`(0,3)\text{.}`]
The line segment from [`(2,3)`] to [`(0,3)`] can be parameterized by
[`\vec{r}(t)=`] [_]{$multians}{15} [@AnswerFormatHelp('vectors')@]* for [_]{$multians}{3} [`\leq t \leq`] [_]{$multians}{3}.
Thus,
[`\displaystyle \int_{C} \left( x\vec{i} -y\vec{j} \right) \cdot d\vec{r}=`] [_]{$integral}{10} [@AnswerFormatHelp('numbers')@]*
END_PGML
############################################################ # Hint ############################################################ #Set value of $showHint in PGcourse.pl for course-wide attempt threshhold for revealing hints
BEGIN_PGML_HINT Parametrize the curve and remember that if [`\vec{r}(t)\text{,}`] for [`a\leq t\leq b\text{,}`] is a smooth parameterization of an oriented curve [`C`] and [`\vec{F}`] is a vector field which is continuous on [`C\text{,}`] then
[``` \int_C \vec{F}\cdot d\vec{r}=\int_a^b \vec{F}(\vec{r}(t))\cdot \vec{r}'(t) dt. ```]
END_PGML_HINT
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION Remember that if [`\vec{r}(t)\text{,}`] for [`a\leq t\leq b\text{,}`] is a smooth parameterization of an oriented curve [`C`] and [`\vec{F}`] is a vector field which is continuous on [`C\text{,}`] then
[``` \int_C \vec{F}\cdot d\vec{r}=\int_a^b \vec{F}(\vec{r}(t))\cdot \vec{r}'(t) dt. ```]
The line segment from [`(2,3)`] to [`(0,3)`] can be parameterized by
[``` \vec{r}(t)=(-2t+2)\vec{i} +3\vec{j},\quad 0\leq t\leq 1 ```]
and we have
[``` \vec{r}'(t)=-2\vec{i} . ```]
Thus,
[```\newcommand{\amp}{&}\begin{aligned} \int_{C} \left( x\vec{i} -y\vec{j} \right) \cdot d\vec{r} \amp = \int_0^1 \left( (-2t+2)\vec{i}-3\vec{j}\right) \cdot \left(-2\vec{i} \right)dt\\ \amp = \int_0^1 4t-4 dt \\ \amp = \left( 2t^2-4t\right)_{0}^{1} \\ \amp = -2. \end{aligned}```]
END_PGML_SOLUTION
############################################################ # End Problem ############################################################
ENDDOCUMENT();

