############################################################
# Body
############################################################

BEGIN_PGML
Evaluate [`\displaystyle \int_{C} \left(x^2\vec{i} - y\vec{j} \right) \cdot d\vec{r}`] where [`C`] is the curve [`y=e^x`] from [`(2,e^2)`] to [`(0,1)\text{.}`]

The curve [`y=e^x`] from [`(2,e^2)`] to  [`(0,1)`] can be parameterized by [`\vec{r}(t)= x(t) \vec{i} + y(t) \vec{j}`] where

[` x(t)= `] [_]{$multians}{10} [@AnswerFormatHelp('formulas')@]*

[` y(t)= `] [_]{$multians}{10} [@AnswerFormatHelp('formulas')@]*

for [_]{$multians}{3} [`\leq t \leq`] [_]{$multians}{3}.

Thus,

[`\displaystyle \int_{C} \left(  x^2\vec{i} -y\vec{j} \right) \cdot d\vec{r}=`] [_]{$integral}{10} [@AnswerFormatHelp('numbers')@]*

END_PGML

############################################################
# Hint
############################################################
#Set value of $showHint in PGcourse.pl for course-wide attempt threshhold for revealing hints

BEGIN_PGML_HINT
Parametrize the curve and remember that if [`\vec{r}(t)\text{,}`] for [`a\leq t\leq b\text{,}`] is a smooth parameterization of an oriented curve [`C`] and [`\vec{F}`] is a vector field which is continuous on [`C\text{,}`] then

[```
                                    \int_C \vec{F}\cdot d\vec{r}=\int_a^b \vec{F}(\vec{r}(t))\cdot \vec{r}'(t)  dt.
                                ```]

END_PGML_HINT

############################################################
# Solution
############################################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
Remember that if [`\vec{r}(t)\text{,}`] for [`a\leq t\leq b\text{,}`] is a smooth parameterization of an oriented curve [`C`] and [`\vec{F}`] is a vector field which is continuous on [`C\text{,}`] then

[```
                                    \int_C \vec{F}\cdot d\vec{r}=\int_a^b \vec{F}(\vec{r}(t))\cdot \vec{r}'(t)  dt.
                                ```]

The curve [`y=e^x`] from [`(0,1)`] to [`(2,e^2)`] can be parameterized by [`t\vec{i}+(e^{t})\vec{j}`] with [`0\leq t\leq 2\text{.}`] To find a parameterization from [`(2,e^2)`] to [`(0,1)`] we reverse the orientation by replacing [`t`] by [`-t\text{.}`] Thus, the curve [`y=e^x`] from [`(2,e^2)`] to  [`(0,1)`] can be parameterized by

[```
                                    \vec{r}(t)=-t\vec{i}+(e^{-t})\vec{j},\quad -2\leq t\leq 0,
                                ```]

and we have

[```
                                    \vec{r}'(t)=-\vec{i} -e^{-t}\vec{j}.
                                ```]

Thus

[```\newcommand{\amp}{&}\begin{aligned}
 \int_{C} \left( x^2\vec{i} - y\vec{j} \right) \cdot d\vec{r} \amp =  \int_{-2}^{0} \left( (-t)^2\vec{i}-(e^{-t})\vec{j}\right) \cdot \left(-\vec{i}-e^{-t}\vec{j} \right)dt\\
 \amp = \int_{-2}^{0} -t^2+e^{-2t}  dt \\
 \amp = \left( -\frac{t^3}{3}-\frac{e^{-2t}}{2}\right)_{-2}^0\\
 \amp = \left( 0-\frac{e^{0}}{2}\right)-\left( -\frac{(-2)^3}{3}-\frac{e^{4}}{2}\right) \\
 \amp = \frac{1}{6}(3 e^4 - 19)\approx 24.132.
\end{aligned}```]

END_PGML_SOLUTION

############################################################
# End Problem
############################################################

ENDDOCUMENT();

