BEGIN_PGML
Evaluate [`\displaystyle \int_{C} \left( y\vec{i} +2x\vec{j} \right) \cdot d\vec{r}`] where [`C`] is the curve [`x=\cos{(y)}`] from [`(1,2\pi )`] to [`(1,0)\text{.}`]

The curve [`C`] can be parameterized by  [`\vec{r}(t)= x(t) \vec{i} + y(t) \vec{j}`] where

[` x(t)= `] [_]{$multians}{10} [@AnswerFormatHelp('formulas')@]*

[` y(t)= `] [_]{$multians}{10} [@AnswerFormatHelp('formulas')@]*

for [_]{$multians}{3} [`\leq t \leq`] [_]{$multians}{3}.

Thus,

[`\displaystyle \int_{C} \left(  y\vec{i} +2x\vec{j} \right) \cdot d\vec{r}=`] [_]{$integral}{10} [@AnswerFormatHelp('numbers')@]*

END_PGML

############################################################
# Hint
############################################################
#Set value of $showHint in PGcourse.pl for course-wide attempt threshhold for revealing hints

BEGIN_PGML_HINT
Parametrize the curve and remember that if [`\vec{r}(t)\text{,}`] for [`a\leq t\leq b\text{,}`] is a smooth parameterization of an oriented curve [`C`] and [`\vec{F}`] is a vector field which is continuous on [`C\text{,}`] then

[```
                                    \int_C \vec{F}\cdot d\vec{r}=\int_a^b \vec{F}(\vec{r}(t))\cdot \vec{r}'(t)  dt.
                                ```]

END_PGML_HINT

############################################################
# Solution
############################################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
Remember that if [`\vec{r}(t)\text{,}`] for [`a\leq t\leq b\text{,}`] is a smooth parameterization of an oriented curve [`C`] and [`\vec{F}`] is a vector field which is continuous on [`C\text{,}`] then

[```
                                    \int_C \vec{F}\cdot d\vec{r}=\int_a^b \vec{F}(\vec{r}(t))\cdot \vec{r}'(t)  dt.
                                ```]

The curve [`x=\cos{(y)}`] from [`(1,0)`] to [`(1,2\pi)`] can be parameterized by [`\cos(t)\vec{i}+t\vec{j}`] with [`0\leq t\leq 2\pi\text{.}`] To find a parameterization from [`(1,2\pi)`] to [`(1,0)`] we reverse the orientation by replacing [`t`] by [`-t\text{.}`] Thus, the curve [`x=\cos{(y)}`] from [`(1,2\pi)`] to  [`(1,0)`] can be parameterized by

[```
                                    \vec{r}(t)=\cos(t)\vec{i}-t\vec{j},\quad -2\pi\leq t\leq 0,
                                ```]

(since [`\cos(-t)=\cos(t)`]), and we have

[```
                                    \vec{r}'(t)=-\sin(t)\vec{i}-\vec{j}.
                                ```]

Thus,

[```\newcommand{\amp}{&}\begin{aligned}
\int_{C} \left(y\vec{i} +2x\vec{j} \right) \cdot d\vec{r} \amp =  \int_{-2\pi}^{0} \left( -t\vec{i}+2\cos(t)\vec{j}\right) \cdot \left(-\sin(t)\vec{i}-\vec{j} \right)dt\\
\amp = \int_{-2\pi}^{0} \left( t\sin(t)-2\cos(t) \right)  dt\\
 \amp =  \left(\sin{(t)} -t\cos{(t)} -2\sin(t)\right)_{-2\pi }^{0} \\
 \amp =  0-\left(0 -(-2\pi)-0\right) \\
 \amp =  -2\pi
\end{aligned}```]

END_PGML_SOLUTION

############################################################
# End Problem
############################################################

ENDDOCUMENT();

